Kowloon's Black Ledger contains the Plague Mandate as the definitive case study for emergency power failure: correct response to a real crisis, incorrect design producing permanent crisis infrastructure.
The Neon Covenant's crisis protocol sunset requirements were directly inspired by the Mandate's failure: every emergency power issued under Covenant authority includes a defined metric that triggers automatic review.
Review is not the same as rescission: the power does not automatically expire at review. The review establishes whether the crisis condition still exists and whether the power is still proportionate.
If the crisis condition has ended but the power has not been rescinded, review flags this as a sunset failure requiring immediate attention.
The Mandate had no review mechanism. Powers were issued. No one was assigned authority to evaluate whether they remained necessary. They remained.
Kowloon's assessment: the Mandate's drafters were not malicious. They were focused on the immediate crisis and assumed someone else would handle the transition. No one was assigned to handle the transition.
The Neon Covenant's crisis protocol assigns transition responsibility explicitly: a designated transition officer holds authority and obligation to initiate rollback when conditions permit.
The officer is designated in the issuing document. The assignment is irrevocable. There is no scenario in which no one is responsible for the transition. The Mandate's failure produced this requirement.
Kowloon's documentation of the Mandate concludes: design the exit before you authorize the entry.

