Kiess's anti-secrecy doctrine treats the Plague Mandate as the most damaging example of emergency power without transparency requirements in the corridor's documented history.
The Mandate's scope was not publicly disclosed at issuance: the specific powers granted were contained in administrative annexes that the affected population did not have access to.
If the people living under the Mandate had known its full scope — including the suspension of lineage-inheritance claims — they could have organized legal challenges before those challenges became impossible.
By the time the Mandate's full scope became publicly known, the powers were embedded in institutional function too complex to challenge through normal legal processes.
Kiess's three-power charter requires that any emergency power be publicly disclosed in full at issuance, with the scope, triggering conditions, and review mechanism all documented and available.
This requirement would have prevented the Mandate's scope concealment. Whether it would have prevented the institutional calcification is less certain.
Kiess's analysis: transparency is necessary but not sufficient. The Mandate could have been fully disclosed and still calcified if the review mechanism was inadequate.
Both requirements — disclosure and sunset — are necessary independently. The Mandate failed both. Most emergency power failures fail one. The Mandate is the extreme case.
Evermeet's lesson plus the Mandate's lesson: institutions that fail from secrecy and institutions that fail from emergency drift are different failures requiring different preventions.

