Rakuen's Garden Ledger treats the Plague Mandate as the foundational document for understanding what Rakuen's disaster-recovery protocols must prevent.
The Mandate responded to a genuine crisis efficiently. The processing infrastructure it created saved lives during the plague period.
When the crisis ended, that infrastructure had no designed transition to peacetime function. It continued operating.
Infrastructure that processes plague dead and crisis detainees operating without crisis conditions becomes infrastructure that processes people without justification.
Rakuen's drawdown protocols specify exactly this transition: when crisis metrics fall below threshold, crisis infrastructure begins managed decommission or repurposing.
Repurposing is preferred over decommission when the infrastructure can serve peacetime functions. The Mandate's infrastructure had no peacetime function — it was designed for extreme crisis processing.
Infrastructure with no peacetime function must be decommissioned when the crisis ends. The Mandate's infrastructure was not. Shadowmere's current state is the result.
Rakuen's disaster-recovery operations include a specific review of infrastructure purpose at every post-crisis assessment: does this serve the recovery, or does it serve the crisis that is now over?
If it serves the crisis, the infrastructure begins decommission. This rule has been applied fourteen times in Rakuen's current governance period. It has produced no Shadowmere outcomes.
Rakuen considers this evidence that the rule works. The rule was designed to prevent Shadowmere. It has prevented fourteen Shadowmeres.

