Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw maintains the Plague Mandate in its oath-violation case files, though the classification is unusual: the Mandate was not itself an oath violation.
The Mandate was a legitimate emergency power. What became oath violations were the individual actions taken under the Mandate's authority once the emergency had passed.
Officers who continued applying cremation orders to non-plague dead, invoking lineage suspension for non-emergency property claims, and using intake authority for political detention had not technically violated the Mandate.
They had violated the conditions under which the Mandate's authority was legitimate, while continuing to invoke that authority.
The Shrine's classification: the Mandate itself is not an oath violation; its continued application outside the conditions that made it legitimate is a sustained oath violation by the officers applying it.
This distinction matters for adjudication: the Mandate cannot be annulled retroactively without voiding legitimate actions taken under it during the crisis period.
But the continued application of the Mandate's powers after the crisis must be adjudicated as separate violations.
Mafdet has no direct jurisdiction over Shadowmere's officers. The Shrine's classification is analytical rather than enforceable from Mafdet.
The Shrine maintains it because the classification is the correct one under oath law, and correct classifications matter even when enforcement is impossible.
The Claw Mark Registry notes: three separate ships' captains from the Mandate period appear in the Registry with oath-violation notations for invoking Mandate authority at Mafdet harbor after the crisis period.
All three were banned from Mafdet's trade network. Their bans remain active.

