Ashborn communities near Shadowmere's frontier zone were directly affected by the Plague Mandate's suspension of lineage-inheritance claims.
The suspension was applied without distinction between community types: Ashborn lineage claims, like all others, were suspended pending plague clearance certification.
Plague clearance certification required documentation that Ashborn communities, which did not use Midgaard's standard documentary practices, could not easily produce.
The suspension therefore lasted longer for Ashborn communities than for human communities with standard documentation, because the clearance pathway was not designed for non-standard documentation practices.
This asymmetric burden was not intentional — no design evidence suggests deliberate targeting — but it was also not corrected when the disparity became apparent.
Ashborn oral history of the Mandate period describes a specific grievance: the emergency powers were applied uniformly across communities, but the exits from those powers were not equally accessible.
Equal application of emergency powers to communities with unequal access to the compliance documentation is not equal treatment. Ashborn communities named this problem at the time.
They named it to Midgaard's intake officers. The intake officers noted the complaint and forwarded it through administrative channels. The channels led to the same administrators who had applied the powers.
The Mandate's complaint mechanism was not independent of the Mandate's administration. Ashborn communities learned this quickly. The lesson persists in Ashborn engagement with Midgaard's administrative systems.
